 be problematic if we're not on Java 9. I could consider importing `java.util.Collections` and using `Collections.singletonList[DiagnosticRelatedInformation](related)` to play it safe.\\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\\"type\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"summary_text\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"text\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"**Clarifying List usage in Java**\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nIt looks like I'm considering the potential conflicts with the dot path when using `List`, but there's no issue. I can safely use the fully qualified `java.util.List.of`, and that seems like the best choice to avoid any naming conflicts. This way, I'm ensuring that there’s no ambiguity in my code, keeping things clear and straightforward. It’s always better to be safe with such matters!\\\\\\\"}]}\\\"}, {\\\"type\\\": \\\"toolCall\\\", \\\"id\\\": \\\"call_gdFSLPNIGAQ7J4OCtiSSofAB|fc_0ffec6755bd7d4050169f133e69380819098bf834545d667f1\\\", \\\"name\\\": \\\"bash\\\", \\\"arguments\\\": {\\\"command\\\": \\\"git diff -- tests/src/org.scala-lang/scala3-interfaces/3.3.1/src/test/scala/org_scala_lang/scala3_interfaces/Scala3_interfacesTest.scala\\\"}}], \\\"api\\\": \\\"openai-responses\\\", \\\"provider\\\": \\\"OCA\\\", \\\"model\\\": \\\"gpt-5.5\\\", \\\"usage\\\": {\\\"input\\\": 2459, \\\"output\\\": 890, \\\"cacheRead\\\": 16384, \\\"cacheWrite\\\": 0, \\\"totalTokens\\\": 19733, \\\"cost\\\": {\\\"input\\\": 0, \\\"output\\\": 0, \\\"cacheRead\\\": 0, \\\"cacheWrite\\\": 0, \\\"total\\\": 0}}, \\\"stopReason\\\": \\\"toolUse\\\", \\\"timestamp\\\": 1777415128766, \\\"responseId\\\": \\\"resp_0ffec6755bd7d4050169f133d9447c819081d2662e86f7b036\\\"}, \\\"toolResults\\\": [{\\\"role\\\": \\\"toolResult\\\", \\\"toolCallId\\\": \\\"call_gdFSLPNIGAQ7J4OCtiSSofAB|fc_0ffec6755bd7d4050169f133e69380819098bf834545d667f1\\\", \\\"toolName\\\": \\\"bash\\\", \\\"content\\\": [{\\\"type\\\": \\\"text\\\", \\\"text\\\": \\\"diff --git i/tests/src/org.scala-lang/scala3-interfaces/3.3.1/src/test/scala/org_scala_lang/scala3_interfaces/Scala3_interfacesTest.scala 